		-- 1.3.6.1.4.1.3715.100.104.1.3.1.3
		networkIPv4InterfaceEnable OBJECT-TYPE
			SYNTAX NetworkInterfacePortEnable
			MAX-ACCESS read-write
			STATUS current
			DESCRIPTION
				"Get and set state of the IPv4 port. Port state can be either enabled (1) or disabled (2).
				
				Command is not interface type specific (Ethernet, IPv4, IPv6, HFC, DOCSIS, USB, DVX etc.). So enabling/disabling IPv4 port may affect IPv6 port too (or may not).
				
				See NetworkInterfacePortEnable type assignment for descriptions.
				
				"
			::= { networkIPv4InterfaceEntry 3 }

		
		-- 1.3.6.1.4.1.3715.100.104.1.3.1.4
		networkIPv4InterfaceServices OBJECT-TYPE
			SYNTAX NetworkInterfaceServices
			MAX-ACCESS read-write
			STATUS current
			DESCRIPTION
				"Get and set service status of IPv4 port.
				
				Supported services: see networkIPv4InterfaceSupportedServices.
				
				Device may support service control per port or just global service enable/disable per device: see networkIPv4InterfaceGlobalServicesEnable.
				
				Services are enabled by networkIPv4InterfaceServices. Enabled service has corresponding service bit set.
				Services are disabled by networkIPv4InterfaceServices. Disabled service has corresponding service bit cleared.
				
				Enabling already enabled service, does not affect service.
				Disabling already disabled service, does not affect service.
				
				NOTE! Enabling or disabling IPv4 services may (or may not) affect IPv6 services. This is device dependant.
				
				NOTE! It is not recommended to disable all services, but to prevent user making device inaccessible, 
				device keeps one service at one port enabled, if all services at all ports of device is going to be 
				disabled. The service and port is device dependent.
				
				See NetworkInterfaceServices type assignment for descriptions."
			::= { networkIPv4InterfaceEntry 4 }

		
